snippet.textDisplay: I love how this song speaks about more than just the loss of the culture of Punjab and Punjabis. The beauty and grace of women diminishing with modernisation and the the fact that many men in their youth are getting into drugs. Also, very importantly the mother tongue is being lost over time with the influence of the west (in their music and media). However, I dont like that most of the examples of the loss in tradition is depicted in a way that points towards women more than men. Therefore, the best part about this is the nostalgia present when they describe their sadness about the division of their land of Punjab, and more so the fact that visiting the other parts of the holy land is very difficult, given tight national border security between India and Pakistan. It is true that Punjab (in India) is perhaps the only state in India that feels the brunt of partition. Chenaab and Raavi are rivers that run mainly through Pakistani Punjab. They ask 'how is Sutluj' which is the river that runs through Indian Punjab, highlighting the yearning, attachment and memory of once having been one. This song completely overlooks political and social hostility, and instead focuses on the love and dream that now seems impossible. Hope this helps. Correct me if I'm wrong.
